Overall Rating:





 Here is how the Allied Home Warranty scam works. They have a "The One-page contract." Three lawyers I showed it to laughed. They said it is one page because it is so vague that it doesn't require Allied to do anything. When you have a problem you will call Allied How Warranty because you think you have a warranty with them and will get some sort of benefit over calling someone else. Wrong. Allied will send our their own contractor. The name on the truck isn't Allied, but they are owned by the same person, Andrew White. The contractor will come out for a $60 fee. You would pay about that if you picked someone at random. You aren't getting a special price. For that $60 Allied's contractor won't actually do any work, but they will over-quote the cost of repairs by as much as three times the actual cost. Then they will tell you that you get a small token credit toward the repair, but only if you use their contractor to do the work. So, if your water heater breaks they may tell you it will be $1,500 to replace it, but they will give you a $300 credit because of your warranty. You could have hired your own repairman to do the whole job for $600, but Allied will not allow this of you want the $300 credit. So, $1,200 for Allied to do the work or $600 to just have it done yourself. The BBB wouldn't even accept my complaint against Allied. The BBB gives them an A+ rating in part because of the low number of complaints they get. The BBB doesn't like to rate its members low because it hurts their business model. Search for "BBB pay for ratings." ABCNews and CNN have both done stories on the BBB scam.

Andrew White established and/or bought Sweat Equity Partners, Allied Warranty, Lone Star Repair, Geovox Security, HomeTool.com, Sweat Energy Services and NRG Energy. They are all the same. view lessHere is how the Allied Home Warranty scam works. They have a "The One-page contract." Three lawyers I showed it to laughed. They said it is one page because it is so vague that it doesn't require Allied to do anything. When you have a problem you will call Allied How Warranty because you think you have a warranty with them and will get some sort of benefit over calling someone else.  ... view more 


